<!-- PERFORMANCE -->
<div style="background: var(--warm-white);">
  <div class="perf-section">
    <div class="section-label">Section 04 — Analysis</div>
    <h2>Reels Are Underperforming.<br><em>What Now?</em></h2>
    <p style="max-width:600px;">Two weeks in, Reels have lower reach-to-engagement conversion than carousels. Here's how I would tackle it.</p>

    <div style="margin: 40px 0 16px">
      <h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans'; font-size:13px; letter-spacing:2px; text-transform:uppercase; font-weight:500; color:var(--muted);">Diagnosis First</h3>
    </div>

    <div class="diagnosis-steps">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Separate reach from engagement</h3>
          <p>Reels might be reaching more accounts but not converting to profile visits or saves. Or they might be getting skipped quickly making high impressions, but low watch-through. These are different problems. I'd pull watch time data, exit points, and compare saves-per-reach across formats before drawing any conclusion.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Check the audience mismatch</h3>
          <p>Reels push to non-followers. If the Reels are reaching people outside the brand's target who aren't design-literate urban millennials, the engagement drop is expected. I'd check the audience demographics on Reel vs carousel reach to see if we're attracting the right people, not just more people.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Audit the first 3 seconds</h3>
          <p>For this brand's slow, cinematic approach, the first frame might not be stopping thumbs in a fast-scroll context. This doesn't mean the content is wrong, it might mean the hook needs rethinking. Does the opening frame have a visual tension or question that earns the watch?</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Consider the nature of the product</h3>
          <p>Homewear may simply be a carousel category. People save and return to "how to style" content. Reels are better for brand feeling, carousels for purchase intent. It is possible both are working, just at different parts of the funnel.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="action-box">
      <h3>What I'd Do Next</h3>
      <ul class="action-list">
        <li>Run one A/B Reel test: same content, different opening frames. One starts on a product, one starts on a person. Track 3-second retention and compare.</li>
        <li>Don't abandon Reels, but recalibrate their job. If carousels are driving saves and site visits, let Reels handle brand discovery (reach). Stop expecting them to do the same thing.</li>
        <li>Try a shorter Reel format (under 20 seconds) for one week. This audience may want long-form content via carousel, not video.</li>
        <li>Add a clear micro-CTA at the 5-second mark — not a hard sell, but a visual or text cue that rewards the viewer for staying. Something as simple as "swipe to see the full space" in caption.</li>
        <li>Revisit audio. If Reels are using music, test one with only ambient sound. If ambient, test one with a well-matched, on-trend audio that still fits the brand.</li>
        <li>Report back to the client with a hypothesis, not just data. "Reels are our discovery engine; carousels are our conversion engine" is a strategic frame they can act on.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>


